column12: “Carbon Fiber Reinforced Plastic A key feature of the innovative BMW LifeDrive concept, the passenger compartment is made of BMW Carbon Fiber Reinforced Plastic (CFRP). Though it is up to 50% lighter than steel and 30% lighter than aluminum, it is an incredibly high-strength material that offers outstanding protection while also offsetting the weight of the electric battery. The innovative BMW LIfeDrive concept forms the framework of all BMW i vehicles, in which two units (the Life Module and the Drive Module) are constructed separately to maximize interior space, achieve 50:50 weight distribution, and lower the center of gravity. Built with the driver in mind, it is revolutionizing car manufacturing.”

column12: “Car has been built from top to bottom. Has 408 engine (6.7L) with a procharger on it (only have it at 6 psi right now). It has a Lunatic crank and rods. JE forged pistons and rings. All of the suspension has been upgraded. Long tube headers to a 4" exhaust to muffler then twin 3" exhaust tips. The trans is a Finish Line Transmission stage 5. It has 5 pinion planetarys and a bunch of billet parts with a vigilante 2800 stall torque convertor. Has new michelon pilot sport tires (335/35/17) in the rear. This engine was built by a mechanic in Nebraska who can go into more detail if you like. Also has 2 fuel pumps with an access panel in the trunk so you don't have to drop the tank. column12: “The car has new tires that are about 16 months old. New oil change done last week that will last for the next 12k miles. New Brakes. All major work has been done by BMW dealership. The car drives and feels like new. Left passenger side door has minor cosmetic damage scrapes as seen in pictures. Very nice looking vehicle interior/exterior. The thing with buying a used X5 is that they have two common problems around this mileage. One is that the valve seals get worn out and the car starts smoking from the tail pipe. To repair this BMW has to take the whole engine apart and it is a $10K job. Another common problem is an oil leak near the timing chain cover. This is another few thousand. On my car all this work has been performed under warranty about a year ago and the warranty paid around $16000 for the repairs. Now this vehicle will drive another 100k miles without those issues ever showing up. For any other issues you get a two year bumper to bumper extended warranty.”

Washer fluid light is on due to leak in reservoir and I have a replacement unit. Just recently the seat belt light came on, no idea what is causing this yet. The fuel level sending unit stops working sporadically, it does not have the 1/4 tank issue that is common, it goes from reading accurately to reading completely empty. I have a new Mopar unit that will come with the truck. The transmission recently started hesitating between 1st and 2nd, easing off the accelerator allows it shift and after that it shifts fine.
